post_text:
One of our featured artists at the gift shop.
Bridge Street Jewelry is a handmade jewelry business headed by Owen Co native Teresa McDonald. All jewelry is handmade with a wide variety to choose from. Their jewelry is made with beads, resin, and original clay pieces. "My love for making jewelry started around 4 years ago. I love to sell at festivals and meeting so many new people. I’m so thankful for all the support I’ve received over the past several years."

All in-stock Bridge Street Jewelry items are an additional 20% off! On our site only. Check it out today! Perfect for Mother's Day Gifts!

shared_text:
The News-Herald
April 9 at 8:18 PM ·

We put out a call to a couple of local artists last week for Owen County and Kentucky themed coloring pages to run in The News-Herald for the next several weeks for the kids who are #HealthyAtHome. The response was amazing! Alli Gill, a senior at Owen County High School, provided this week's artwork of the Owen County Courthouse. If you saw the print edition of the newspaper, we also included a brief history of the courthouse to provide kids with a little lesson to go along with the fun. Feel free to print the coloring page and send us a photo of your child with their artwork, or use the page that was in the newspaper. The pictures should be sent to mhaines@owentonnewsherald.com. We will create an online gallery to showcase the pages we receive. Happy coloring!

shared_text:
Faith Clifton is with Mark Mcmillen and 17 others.
October 26, 2019 at 9:17 AM ·

Tickets are in for the 3rd annual performance of Owen County Community Theatre's production of "A Mayberry Christmas"! Tickets are offered for a donation and will be available at our ticket office, the lobby of the old OC courthouse. There is a limit of 6 per household. The ticket office is open on Tuesdays and Thursdays during our rehearsal, from 6:30-8:00 pm (closed on Halloween for Trick or Treat). A limited number of tickets will also be available at the Owen County Tourism office beginning Wednesday, October 30.

post_text:
We have some very exciting news!
Owen County Tourism is getting a new home in town and adding an artisan retail gift shop! With the gracious efforts of Bell's Boutique, we are moving into their location and adding a gift shop for Owen County merchandise and a local artist to display and sell their products! We hope to be re-open mid-April and plan on opening 7 days a week through the spring and summer. Follow this page for posts on the progress. In the meantime, if you have any suggestions for local talent or are a local artist and would like to retail your work please message us here.

post_text: Happening in New Columbus on Sunday March 3rd!
shared_text:
Pat Wright
February 22, 2019 at 11:06 PM ·

Save the date MARCH 3, 2019! This year Owen County celebrates 200 years. New Columbus is celebrating our community on March 3 from 3pm - 5pm. The Bicentennial torch will travel to our community and will reside in the parking lot adjacent to New Columbus Methodist Church until March 31. Beginning at 3 the festivities continue at the New Columbus Baptist Church. We will have a guest speaker, Georgia Green Stamper, writer/historian from this community. There will be a display of historical items that depict early days of our community. Everyone is invited to help us celebrate!! Look forward to seeing you. No

shared_text:
Owen County 4-H Fair & Horse Show
January 21, 2019 at 9:56 PM ·

Owen County Fair Board Secretary, Lindsey Tirey, accepting two awards from Agriculture Commissioner, Ryan Quarles & the Department of Agriculture during Saturday’s business meeting at the Kentucky Association of Fairs & Horse Shows annual convention.
First award is the All Kentucky Fair Award which is given to all fairs who pay the maximum allowable amount on all premiums for exhibits & livestock shows.
The second award is for first place in the catalog competition, in the Class C Non-Glossy, Non-Slick Cover category. Each year the fair board submits a copy of our fair catalog to the department of ag for judging. This award would not be possible without our long standing partnership with the Owenton News-Herald. And a special thanks to 4th grader, Tyler Cammack, for providing the artwork on the 2018 fair catalog cover!

shared_text:
Owen County, KY Bicentennial
January 16, 2019 at 3:19 PM ·

DO YOU REMEMBER? 25 years ago this week, a massive winter storm struck Owen County, dumping 16-20 inches of snow Jan. 16, 1994. A number of local businesses were forced to close for about three days. Many residents, like the ones pictured here, walked to town to buy their groceries. What can you remember about the "Storm of 1994?"(Photo courtesy of The News-Herald)
